### Describe the problem that you experienced

I have a feeling this may be an angular 'design bug' unless perhaps there is a hook to catch the unreported primary exception to me (error handler is receiving the 2ndary unimportant exception).

Docs need a better set pattern on global exception handling.  Perhaps code needs to pass the CustomErrorHandler TWO exceptions in the case of primary/secondary as today it received the 2ndary render exception and not the primary exception which was the original cause(ie. without the primary, the 2ndary would not happen).  I spent hours on this before I finally found out what is going on (much because I was never given the primary exception and was given something in left field) -> 

In my init method of my component we have this 

```
        this._proposalSvc.proposalXref$
            .pipe(takeUntil(this._unsubscribeAll))
            .subscribe((response: FetchProposalXrefResponse) => {
                this.xrefResponse = response;

                if (
                    this.xrefResponse.outline.trainingFormat ===
                    ClassFormatEnumDto.MULTI_DAY
                ) {
                    this.isMultiDay = true;
                }

                this.statusInfo = new StatusInfo();
                this.statusInfo.projectName = response.outline?.projectName;
                this.statusInfo.stage = response.courseStage;
                this.statusInfo.hasCredits = true;
                this.statusInfo.creditsLeft = response?.customerCreditsLeft;

                this.statusInfo.avatar = new AvatarInfo();
                this.statusInfo.avatar.chatId = response.proposalXref?.xrefId;
                this.statusInfo.avatar.link = response?.otherParty?.avatar;
                this.statusInfo.avatar.firstName =
                    response?.otherParty?.firstName;
                this.statusInfo.avatar.lastName =
                    response?.otherParty?.lastName;

                this.calculateIfAvailable();
            });
```

Now, if you throw an exception on the LAST line, GREAT!!!  If you throw an exception on the FIRST line, it will be hidden by a render exception.  Worse yet, the customErrorHandler is never told about the primary exception and that is the one we care about and need to fix ASAP.    The 2ndary can be fixed but not as important by making things optional in the html (things that are actually required but on failure will not be there).     

If you know of 'javas' try with resource,  try (stream str = openStream()) { .....code here }, it secretly has a stream.close() surrounded with a try..catch to not lose the primary exception.  it then adds the 'supressed' 2ndary exception to the primary so you have both (and you end up with array of suppression but the global error handler ends up with the primarys which has supressedErrors[].  Java also has chained exceptions.  this is when you catch, rethrow new Exception("my chain", e); such that the new error links to old one (realy only for adding info that may only be available near the top of stack to the message.  (Do not confuse supressed and chained...two different concepts).

I would love suppressed in the case of render failures!!!  

I would LOVE to know if it was a render failure so I can just move the user to a solid bug page that I know will render cleanly.  



